Construction of the large New England Clean Energy Connect hydropower converter station off outer Main Street in Lewiston is seen in its final phase in February 2025. The transmission line is expected to begin commercial operation Friday. (Russ Dillingham/Staff Photographer)

The project’s fate was put to voters in a 2021 referendum. During the campaign, proponents and opponents spent a combined [$100 million](https://www.pressherald.com/2021/11/02/hotly-contested-power-line-brings-out-maine-voters/) to sway opinion, setting a new record for ballot questions in the state.

Voters decisively [sided against the project](https://www.centralmaine.com/2021/11/02/hotly-contested-power-line-brings-out-maine-voters/?_gl=1*151cbrq*_gcl_au*MTIzNDYxMTIyMS4xNzQ0ODk0MzM2*_ga*OTgxODkxMDQzLjE3MjEzNDg4MzE.*_ga_ZYHMH0BHHB*czE3NDc5MjUwNDUkbzQ4NCRnMCR0MTc0NzkyNTA1MSRqNTQkbDAkaDAkZFFzd050d0QtaFJ5VWcydUZ6ZTQ4ZnZkU084bE5hSGEzTmc.), but Avangrid argued that the referendum’s retroactive approach was unconstitutional. The court ultimately [sided with the utility](https://www.centralmaine.com/2022/08/30/supreme-court-sends-cmp-corridor-case-back-to-lower-court/).

